export const batch121 = {
  'competitive-strategy.json': {
    base: { id: 'competitive-strategy', title: 'Competitive Strategy', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781613021010 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Every business runs on some form of strategy',
        text: "A company's shape and setup shape the way it competes. A small local dairy and a large national creamery will look very different on the inside. A strategy is a bundle of policies aimed at reaching specific goals. A clear strategy gets written down and signed off by top leaders. Even when nothing is written, the company still has a strategy in practice. An unspoken strategy grows out of what each team or person tries to do for what they see as the long term. Those small local moves rarely line up with the best design for the whole company.\n\nLong range planning helps you see where the business is likely to head. As a leader, you can press on a few core questions.\n\nWhat forces are pushing the industry you want to enter. How is the industry itself likely to change. What moves are rivals preparing to make. What is the strongest counter move. How can the firm stay ahead over time.\n\nThe habit of planning shows there are real benefits to chase. Still, formal planning often raises the right questions without giving the right answers. Most tools that try to answer them, usually sold by consulting firms, dive into the inside of one company instead of looking at the wider industry."
      },
      {
        title: 'The pull of fresh rivals',
        text: "An industry is a group of companies that sell goods or services that are close substitutes for each other. The push and pull inside an industry drags the return on invested capital toward the lowest acceptable level.\n\nBuyers grow more sensitive to price when goods are similar and cost a lot relative to income. As Michael E. Porter, PhD has noted.\n\nNewcomers often bring deep pockets and a strong wish to grab market share. They may cut prices, which makes rivals look pricey by comparison. Profits can shrink across the board. Whether new players show up depends on how hard the field fights back and the natural economic walls around the industry.\n\nSome of those walls are well known. Scale economies force new players to start big and face retaliation, or to start small and carry a cost burden. Both paths hurt. Product differentiation forces new players to spend heavily to break old loyalties. Capital demands require large sums, especially for uncertain ad or research budgets. Switching costs hit buyers only once, when they jump from one supplier to another. Distribution access means new players must beg for shelf space or screen time, and they often pay for the chance through discounts or ad support. Government rules can also cap access to raw materials or require special licenses.\n\nSwitching costs can include retraining staff or buying new gear."
      },
      {
        title: 'Three broad paths to beat the field',
        text: "Even inside one industry, firms selling similar things can look very different in their bones. That structure points the firm toward a specific approach. Three general paths show up again and again, and they can be shaped to fit your own situation.\n\nOverall cost leadership puts cost at the center. Cutting cost is the main job. You run the plant in the leanest way and drop customers who barely pay their way. The biggest savings usually come from research, service, sales, and advertising.\n\nResearch and ads are key to gaining the edge, but cutting cost also gives a real advantage. It keeps prices low while still letting you earn a return. When your costs are low, even powerful buyers cannot move them. The same goes for powerful suppliers. Low cost also calls for a large share of the market and steady access to raw materials. AliExpress, Alibaba, Amazon, McDonald's, and Wizz Air are well known examples of cost leadership done well.\n\nSavings from cost leadership can fund better tools and equipment.\n\nDifferentiation is your chance to stand out. You do not have to be unique in every way, only in key areas like design, brand image, service, technology, or features. Apple wins on operating system, design, and the feel of higher quality at a higher price. Emirates wins on service and technology. Hermes wins on rare, original, hard to find goods. Tesla wins on innovation, green focus, and the lack of a marketing push. Lush wins on handmade, ethical, and social values.\n\nThe wish to own something rare and original often beats a wish to save money. Buyers who value that kind of brand stick with it, because they feel the company made the product for them. That is why higher prices feel fair. A clear differentiation message tells the buyer the product is not for everyone, and it is worth it.\n\nYou can fund differentiation through better service, research, and advertising.\n\nFocus means picking a narrow group, a narrow product line, or a narrow region. Each team builds policies that match the whole industry but aim at a small slice. Cost cutting or differentiation both fit under focus. Whichever path you pick, you still need a little something extra, like a special benefit or a wider range of choices within the niche.\n\nWhen the focus is on cost, the product should be useful every day, not rare. Everyday items always have demand. When the focus is on being unique, you aim at a narrow slice and try to sharpen the special idea. In that case, the extra value may come from meeting individual needs or tailoring the product for each customer.\n\nA low cost position usually gives the firm a better spot against substitutes when compared to its rivals. As Michael E. Porter, PhD has written."
      },
      {
        title: 'Four lenses for reading your rivals',
        text: "Four key elements make up a strong competitor review.\n\nFuture goals are where the firm wants to end up, and they shape how the company acts in the market. They also tell you whether the rival is happy where they stand. They may want to change course because of inner issues or outside pressure. Goals reveal how ready they are to make a fresh move or stick to what they know.\n\nA simple question opens the door. Who are our real rivals in this industry.\n\nTo get a clear read on what a rival wants now and later, ask a few pointed questions. What are their stated and hidden financial targets. Do they lean toward short term wins or long term growth. How do they feel about taking risks. Do they want to lead the industry. Do they carry values beyond profit.\n\nA read on a rival's goals helps you predict how they will respond when you change your own moves.\n\nAssumptions are beliefs the team holds without needing proof. They fall into two main groups.\n\nHow a rival sees itself can rest on image rather than fact. An oil firm may plant trees in South America to look like a defender of nature, while its main work still drills the seabed and harms coral. The image and the real work do not match.\n\nHow a rival sees the industry and other firms can also miss reality. Before you take that view at face value, keep a few ideas in mind. You can never know exactly what the customer wants. Ads and social media are not pure wins. Trends that look like they will last can vanish in a flash. Customers come in many shapes and are not equal. Loyalty does not always mean big profit.\n\nCurrent strategy was covered earlier as the explicit or implicit set of policies aimed at company goals.\n\nCapabilities cover the resources a rival has, like time, money, and the speed of their response. Strengths and weak spots shape how well they can react to change, start a move of their own, or handle shifts in the wider world or the industry itself."
      },
      {
        title: 'Survival tactics for split markets',
        text: "When no single firm leads the market, the industry is fragmented. A clear leader usually sets the pace and shapes the rivalry. Another tell is that medium sized firms make up most of the field. Services, retail, distribution, wood and metal work, farm products, and creative fields often look like this.\n\nIndustries split for reasons that often add up. The main ones are low entry walls, which invite a flood of new players. High transport costs, which limit how far a firm can reach. Local rules, which set standards and force firms to follow regional politics. A focus on close service, which works best with a small team that knows the customer well.\n\nLocal rules can drive fragmentation all on their own.\n\nFour moves can fight back against fragmentation. Address the main causes of fragmentation, since a few specific factors often do most of the splitting, and managing them can pull the market back together. Anticipate industry shifts, because consolidation tends to happen as industries grow up, especially when the early split came from novelty or when outside trends change the picture. Bring market needs closer to one standard, by using product or marketing innovation to merge different tastes into one offer, much like custom styles that fit many. Build scale or learning curve benefits, because new technology can spread fixed costs across more units, and scale in one part of the business can cover the lack of it elsewhere."
      },
      {
        title: 'The test facing brand new industries',
        text: "Fresh industries are born from new tech, fresh customer needs, or shifts in the market.\n\nA few structural facts tend to define them at this stage. The tech is still shaky. No one has settled on the right strategy. Upfront costs are high and savings come slowly.\n\nBecause the market is new and production runs are small, cost cuts tend to come at a slow pace.\n\nA few problems hold the industry back. Getting raw materials and parts can be tough. Raw material prices can jump without warning. The wider support system is often missing. Buyers can feel lost.\n\nEven with the risks, there are ways to soften the path and even get ahead of the pack. You can be the first to step onto the field. It is risky, but entry walls can be very low, and you will be the first to plant your brand in the market. Another way is to set the rules of the game. You can do this if your marketing or pricing is hard to beat. New players sometimes have to fight a strategy they do not like, but when your footing is solid, you can sharpen and grow your own approach. Moving mobility walls and reshaping the role of suppliers and channels are also good early steps to lock in your place.\n\nA useful note: new firms that bring fresh products to the market can often count on support from government or other public bodies through grants and tax breaks."
      },
      {
        title: 'Moves for industries in slow decline',
        text: "An industry is in decline when it has missed its sales target for a long stretch. A short miss is just part of a normal cycle. Over time, demand for some goods or services fades and may vanish for a few clear reasons.\n\nTech substitution is one. Picture a typewriter maker that had a steady business for years, then personal computers flooded the market. The old machines may have value for collectors, but not enough collectors to keep a business alive.\n\nDemographics is another. The world's population is aging, and the trend will run on for years. Retirees tend to have less buying power, and place matters too. For a gadget, areas with younger people are stronger targets.\n\nShifts in needs come from many places. Wars and armed conflicts push demand for weapons. Pandemics push demand for personal protection gear.\n\nThe kinds of buyers who still want a product can shape whether it lives or fades.\n\nA decline is not always a death sentence. Firms often pull back and harvest as a way to cut costs. Porter still lays out a few strategic options, though they are not one size fits all.\n\nLeadership makes sense when the industry is fading but still has some demand. Your firm may be the last one standing or one of a few. You can take out rivals by buying their share or by spending hard to grow your own.\n\nNiche means finding a slice or a demand pocket, as Porter calls it, and pouring effort into keeping it. Leadership tactics help here too.\n\nHarvest means tuning the cash flow and keeping the revenue. You can do this by cutting new spending, trimming upkeep on the plant, and putting money into the areas most likely to pay off."
      },
      {
        title: 'Closing thoughts',
        text: "Industry structure, captured in five forces (new entry, the threat of substitutes, the bargaining power of buyers, the bargaining power of suppliers, and rivalry among current rivals), gives a way to think about how value should be made and split among the players, new and old. The frame shows that competition runs wider than the fight with current rivals. Drawing the edges of an industry can be fuzzy, but one of the five forces almost always names the core challenge of sharing value. A sixth force, possibly led by government or by tech, is up for debate. Still, its weight cannot be measured well when the other five are out of the picture.\n\nPorter offers three general strategies any firm can weigh as it grows and fights for share. They are broad, but can be shaped to fit the firm. He also looks at fresh industries, with the spark of novelty but without large runs, that have not had time to win over buyers. He turns to declining industries too, where some share is still up for grabs. Porter lays out how to chase it.\n\nA short set of questions to try. What are the current demographic trends where you live. Do they match the global picture. How do they shape the buying power of your future customers. Will people want your product or service in ten years. How about fifty. Is it a basic need or a special one. Has anyone else already made it. If not, ask yourself why. If yes, ask how to beat them. Build a set of standards to judge the success of your product or service. Set the bar that tells you when the business needs to be shut down or reshaped, since stopping at the right time is always the smart call."
      }
    ]
  },

  'console-wars.json': {
    base: { id: 'console-wars', title: 'Console Wars', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781656939336 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'How the console came to be',
        text: "Video games are a huge part of daily life now, from phones to home consoles. They pull in large sums of money, fuel the economy, and bring fun to millions. They were not always so polished.\n\nBack then, playing a video game meant sitting alone at a personal computer. The idea of a console, or of sharing a screen with friends, felt far off, almost a dream. For some, that dream became a steady push to make it real.\n\nThe video game industry grew slowly at first, but the spark was there from the start.\n\nIn the 1950s, the first signs of home consoles began to appear. They were just simple games that ran on several computers, far from what we know today, but they pointed the way for anyone who wanted to share a screen. The seed of the console was planted.\n\nThose early tries to bring games into the home cleared the path for the console to be born.\n\nRalph Baer built the first working console. He named it the Brown Box, and it came with games ranging from checkers to several sports. It used switches and program cards so the player could pick the game. His work moved gaming into the living room and gave others a model to follow.\n\nThe console wars truly took off when the first home console was sold in 1977, but the real heavy hitters had not joined yet.\n\nThe design was so clever that others tried to copy it. In 1977, the first to make a real splash was Atari, founded by Nolan Bushnell. The original name was the Video Computer System, but buyers knew it as the Atari 2600. Atari had a strong run, but it ended up as a side note in the long arc of the console wars. The next chapters dig into the fights and the surprises that brought other brands to the top. Every war has winners and losers, and the next chapters show how fast the lead can change hands."
      },
      {
        title: 'The first shakeout and Nintendo rises',
        text: "What looked like a golden age for gaming turned into a bloodbath. After Atari opened the door, other firms piled in to chase the best home console. The floodgates swung wide, and the shelves filled with consoles of wildly different quality.\n\nThe arrival of the Atari console made space for many new companies and their machines.\n\nThe new wave included Mattel, Coleco, and Nintendo. With all of them in play, you would expect a real fight, but most of them were in too much of a rush, churning out game after game. That rush would hurt the market as a whole.\n\nNew firms tried to grab a slice of the video game money, but they let quality slip.\n\nThe market paid the price for the flood. Games shipped with less care, less polish, and less pull. Buyers did not line up for the new releases, and those who bought them stopped playing fast. Sales sank, the gold rush ended, and many firms hit the floor.\n\nThe crash in the video game market cleared a path for Nintendo to grab the lead.\n\nNintendo came in with sharp marketing and a fresh take on design. They set out to reset what the American buyer expected from a console, in a pool of look alike machines. The result was the Nintendo Entertainment System, one of the sharpest 8 bit consoles of its time, and a release that locked Nintendo in as a true giant of the field. The NES had the market to itself for years, since no one else could stand up to a crash that had wiped the floor.\n\nBy 1990, Nintendo of America had sold close to thirty million consoles. One in three U.S. homes owned an NES, as Blake J. Harris notes."
      },
      {
        title: 'Sega shows up swinging',
        text: "Nintendo had become a giant of the field, with sharper graphics and a stronger game line up than anyone else. They kept the lead for six years, raking in profit in the United States and abroad. Nintendo looked unbeatable, or so it seemed.\n\nWith no real challenger, Nintendo ran the table and pulled in record profits through the 1990s.\n\nThen Sega came along. Sega was not brand new, but the brand had not yet built the kind of name that made players care. Nintendo, sitting on top, would need a real plan and strong products to be knocked down. Sega was ready.\n\nSega arrived as the new kid and gave Nintendo a real fight.\n\nIn 1993, Sega pushed a hard hitting campaign for the Sega Genesis. It was a straight attack on the public image of Nintendo and the NES. The Genesis offered sharper graphics, more game modes, fresher titles, and a faster feel. Sega was there to stay, and not in a quiet way.\n\nSega had to pull out all the stops to break Nintendo's grip.\n\nThat was the start of the console wars. Two giants dug in for a fight at home and abroad. Nintendo still held the lead in foreign markets, but Sega's bold ads and packaging gave American buyers a fresh feel they had been waiting for.\n\nAs Blake J. Harris puts it, video games were for everyone, and people were about to figure that out."
      },
      {
        title: 'Sony steps in and rewrites the fight',
        text: "As the video game industry grew and Sega and Nintendo kept selling, more serious players lined up to grab the throne. At the front of the pack was the Japanese firm Sony. Sony had first tried to work with Nintendo as a partner. Seeing the brand and the profit ahead, Sony offered to bring CD technology into the consoles that still used cartridges.\n\nSony first wanted to ride the wave, not shape it, by helping Nintendo grow.\n\nThe deal fell apart, and the two firms went cold. From the ashes of that broken tie, a fresh idea was born. Sony had wanted to help Nintendo add CDs, but they also wanted to bring players into 3D graphics, since the rivals were still locked in 2D.\n\nNintendo felt that a switch to CDs would hurt its image.\n\nAfter Nintendo said no, choosing to lean on what was already working, Sony saw its own shot and took it. They built a console with CDs and 3D graphics, and they called it the PlayStation. Its launch opened a new chapter for the industry and the console wars, which had lived in a flat 2D world for years. Sony was set to take over, and they did, in a big way.\n\nSony went back to the drawing board and turned their old offer into the PlayStation.\n\nNintendo still earned its share of the money, but Sega crashed hard when it tried to copy Sony's CD approach. Sega's machine sold a weak 9.5 million units. Sony topped that in the first year alone, with over 100 million units, well above Nintendo's 33 million. A new war had begun, and a new player had the bigger arsenal and was not pulling punches.\n\nA side note for the history books: Nintendo invented the D-Pad back in 1982."
      },
      {
        title: 'The price of losing ground',
        text: "As the war kept going, the older players fought to stay in the game. While Sega and Nintendo struggled to hold on to their buyers, Sony swept the streets and left little for anyone else.\n\nWith fresh tech on their side, Sony pulled in record profits and left only scraps for the rest of the field.\n\nSony released the PlayStation 2 in 2000, and it went on to become the highest selling console of all time, with a massive 150 million units moved. The win came from steady invention and a willingness to grow with the times. They moved on from the CD era of the first PlayStation to DVD in the PlayStation 2, giving players hands on access to a new kind of media that was spreading fast.\n\nOwning a PlayStation meant owning the newest tech on the block, and that gave Sony a real edge. The DVD upgrade locked in their lead and forced the field to try to copy it. Sega kept trying to match Sony, putting out the Sega Genesis in 1988, a console that worked with CDs but did not reach Sony's level. The Sega Dreamcast in 1998 was their last try, and the last console they would make before they stepped out of the war. Their exit left room for new players to jump in.\n\nAfter a long run of failed comebacks, Sega had to call it quits.\n\nMicrosoft stepped in with the first Xbox, right as Sega officially stepped out of the race on March 1, 2001. Nintendo kept chasing with the GameCube. Neither of them sold enough to worry Sony, since Sony had the new golden goose, the PlayStation 2."
      },
      {
        title: 'The modern fight and old names return',
        text: "Years passed, and Sony was no stranger to big wins, but it was not shy about a fresh fight. The new challenger came from Microsoft and its well known Xbox line. Xbox learned from the first model and worked to match Sony on tech and on the range of games.\n\nMicrosoft learned from past mistakes and pushed harder to make better consoles.\n\nSony kept its pace and released the PlayStation 3. Microsoft answered with the Xbox 360, a close match that carried one extra benefit. It was cheaper. Sony leaned on its brand and tried to squeeze every last dollar from buyers. The high price on the PlayStation 3 opened the door for the Xbox 360 to grab ground.\n\nThat move locked in Microsoft as a real player in the new console wars and started a rivalry that is still alive today. In the middle of that fight, an older name was plotting a comeback, and it was only a matter of time before it found its moment.\n\nIn November 2006, Nintendo rose from the ashes with the Wii, a simple but brilliant machine. Nintendo did not want to fight on raw tech or design. Instead, it brought a fresh twist. While Microsoft and Sony were squaring off on specs, Nintendo gave players a clear, easy design that anyone could pick up.\n\nNintendo shot back to the top with smart marketing and fresh thinking.\n\nThat choice meant the Wii reached more than the usual buyer. Grandparents and kids picked it up as easily as core gamers. Nintendo climbed back to the top, free from the spec war that Sony and Microsoft were stuck in, and sold over 100 million units worldwide.\n\nToday, Sony and Microsoft have found ways to compete without losing buyers over the price tag. The fight goes on. The rules of the game stay the same, but the weapons will keep changing. Who knows. A new player could step up and unseat the three giants, Sony, Microsoft, and Nintendo."
      },
      {
        title: 'Looking back',
        text: "The console wars were born from a need to bring the joy of gaming into the living room, in a simple, ready to use form. The console was the result of years of hard work and research. But the invention led to a rough kind of competition. The first to make a stand was Atari in 1977, but that only opened the door for more players, and a flood of products hit the market.\n\nSome of those products, if not all, were rushed and weak. Quality was an afterthought. The reckless pace helped cause the crash.\n\nThe crash left no one standing and cleared a path for a fresh challenger to step in. Nintendo made its first move in the console wars with the Nintendo Entertainment System, then a cut above the rest. The NES thrived until it owned the video game market, with over 50 million units sold at home and abroad. With that giant running the show, you would think no one would dare to fight back, but the size of the target only made it more attractive. Sega came in from Japan and made itself heard by going after the top dog, Nintendo, and that started the first real rivalry. The fight grew into a full war, and Sega crashed and burned when better armed rivals, Sony and Microsoft, joined the field. Sony and Microsoft are still the ones to beat.\n\nAs Blake J. Harris writes, video games were not just for kids. They were for anyone who wanted to feel like a kid again.\n\nA short note to try. Sony keeps the lead by working hard to make the best gaming experience, and for this writer, they are the standout pick. You should make up your own mind. Who knows. One day we may end up on the same virtual team or fighting a cosmic giant side by side."
      }
    ]
  },

  'contagious.json': {
    base: { id: 'contagious', title: 'Contagious', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781613111489 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Look at your business with fresh eyes',
        text: "Modern businesses and marketing campaigns should chase a useful kind of virality. You can set a strong example in a few ways. Find a fresh way to reach your audience, the way Steve Jobs did. Understand the real wishes of your customers, the way social worker Koreen Johannessen does. Surprise your buyers, the way Blendtec's Tom Dickson or journalist Denise Grady does. Pull people in with a one of a kind experience, the way the owners of the Please Don't Tell bar do.\n\nVery few things go viral by accident. Most of the time, virality is the result of a careful plan that takes care of current buyers and pulls in new ones.\n\nThe recipe is not hidden. People will pay attention to your services and pass them along when the products make them feel better. If your work stirs up good feelings and brings something new and useful, the spread grows fast. If you can also place your brand's story inside the wider story of human life and earn social proof, you will hold the keys to virality.\n\nStudy your audience, watch what your partners build, and try new things without fear. Most of all, enjoy your work. That energy will pass on to your customers.\n\nA quick exercise. Put your idea to the test and lay out a plan to spread it. How many people know about it today. How will it make their lives better. What feelings does your product bring, and what story does it tell. Why would people want to tell others about it."
      },
      {
        title: 'Mystery pulls in fans of rare finds',
        text: "Most people have a few favorite places to meet friends. They know where to grab a healthy breakfast, where to find the best pizza, and where the beer is cheapest. On one hand, these spots save time and cut down on choices. On the other hand, the same cafes can grow stale, and people start craving something new.\n\nHas that ever happened to you. Picture this. You and your friends are talking about a new place, and a stranger at the next table tells you about a secret bar. You will not find it on a map, but they will lead the way. First, you step into an old phone booth and dial a special code.\n\nWhy should you care. A new bar or restaurant opens somewhere every week, and most of them push hard with bright ads, glowing reviews, and the widest reach. New restaurateurs will do whatever it takes to please visitors. That is not always what buyers want.\n\nIn a world where almost anything is easy to find, some people value being different even more. They chase the chance to see, buy, and own something that others have not heard of.\n\nGetting a peek at rare products, places, and events lifts a person's confidence and standing.\n\nBy the way, the bar from the start of the chapter is real. It is called Please Don't Tell, and it sits in New York. It is hard to find unless you know the regulars or the owners. Please Don't Tell is not trying to win over the whole city. There would not be room for everyone, and the bar prizes its air of mystery. That is why it has the highest social currency.\n\nHopefully, this story shows you when it might make sense to keep a few updates quiet so that your audience wants to know more. Sometimes, less really is more."
      },
      {
        title: 'Marketing at a sprint or a marathon',
        text: "What do people talk about more, their adventures and wild moments, or the everyday stuff of life. You are right if you said it depends on how boring their day was. Who wants to chat about favorite oatmeal or toothpaste when they can share travel stories and discoveries.\n\nStill, a study by Jonah Berger's team found that people are more likely to talk about everyday topics, just because most days are ordinary. There is nothing wrong with that. In fact, the finding opens the door to more research, especially for ad campaigns.\n\nWhy. Because many brands chase attention. Of course, the Please Don't Tell bar does the opposite and works hard to stay secret. Yet countless companies dream of landing on personal recommendation lists, slipping into friendly chats, and catching a wave of word of mouth at any cost.\n\nFirms that lean on word of mouth stand out from those chasing the usual ad game.\n\nAt the same time, it helps to know that different services need different speeds of spread. For a new restaurant, reaching a lot of people fast is critical, or it will struggle against the established spots.\n\nOn the other hand, fast reach is not always the point for elections or social campaigns. Businesses or individuals can still gain when their ideas sit in people's minds longer, so the audience can make the right call at the right time. Even when people disagree or push back against the idea, the idea keeps its grip on their attention.\n\nTo go viral, skip the loud slogans and pick the right triggers that spark a reaction. Watch the places where people live, listen to what they talk about and use, and make your services interesting enough that they have no reason to say no."
      },
      {
        title: 'Use ordinary topics to spark real interest',
        text: "In 2008, Denise Grady's article about coughing landed on The New York Times Most E Mailed list. She did not write about cats, cartoons, or cruises. She wrote about a cough. And thousands of people forwarded it to family, friends, and coworkers in one go. Let us look at why.\n\nSave articles, notes, messages, and books that make you think. Come back to them when you need a fresh spark or a new idea.\n\nIn the first phase of research on articles that end up on the Most E Mailed list, Jonah Berger's team found that health and education topics were the most popular. That alone did not explain Grady's success.\n\nThe next phase built the numbers, and they showed that useful and interesting pieces had a 30 percent edge that helped them land on the list. That part made sense and was probably obvious to the author. Why else write a paper about a cough with no value.\n\nThe research took a fresh turn when Berger and his team looked closely at the feelings of readers. They found that people love to learn secrets and life hacks from writers, and that surprise and delight made them want to share. The chance to be the source of those cool facts pushed people to forward the articles to their circle.\n\nThe secret of Grady's piece was that it showed a familiar act, coughing, from a fresh angle. People were so taken with the new facts that they did not want to be the only ones in the know.\n\nWhen we care, we share, as Jonah Berger has written.\n\nStrong negative feelings can also pull people together and hold their attention. To pull this off, you have to highlight the right angles and lay out your point of view clearly. Pieces that stir sadness tend to slip by almost unnoticed.\n\nSo, put good energy into your messages. Stir up a sense of wonder, and people will talk about you.\n\nA side note. Albert Einstein, the Nobel Prize winner in physics, saw the bridge between art and science as his deepest source of inspiration and wonder. He believed that anyone could find reasons to marvel, even in the dullest or hardest subject."
      },
      {
        title: 'People copy the ones they admire',
        text: "Next time you feel like you are wasting your time, remember that Steve Jobs and his partner Ken Segall spent long hours on the placement of the Apple logo on their machines.\n\nThe small talk made sense because they were weighing another driver of virality, public visibility. They had to pick between two priorities. Serving the current customer or pulling in a new one. Depending on the choice, the Apple logo on the laptop would either look at the user when they opened the lid, or it would face outward toward the people around them. Jobs and Segall went with the second option.\n\nIn public, people watch, judge, and compare. They notice what strangers wear, buy, eat, and talk about. If they like what they see, they quietly copy it and think about what they need to match those around them.\n\nThat is why fashion designers, restaurateurs, directors, writers, and trainers all want to land on recommendation lists. When most people agree on the quality and value of a service, it becomes a must have for everyone else.\n\nSocial proof runs on the fact that people watch what others do and feel good about before making similar choices.\n\nThe pull of public behavior on private habits matters not only for businesses but also for social campaigns. The work of clinical social worker Koreen Johannessen at the University of Arizona shows this in action.\n\nWhile studying youth drinking and looking for ways to cut it, she found that flyers and stats about the harm from alcohol did not move the students at all. Private talks with students pointed to the real issue. Most of them did not like getting drunk, but the topic of parties and binges came up so often in friend groups that they thought everyone was drinking. That insight let Johannessen strip alcohol of its place as the top tool for socializing.\n\nBehavior is public and thoughts are private, as Jonah Berger has written."
      },
      {
        title: 'Show the practical value of what you offer',
        text: "People are always looking for ways to be more productive, save time or money, sharpen their skills, or boost their well being. The strongest pull, though, comes when a product or service makes them look smart in front of friends and family for recommending it.\n\nBy sharing high quality, useful information, you can become a go to resource and raise the odds of your ideas spreading.\n\nSo another solid route to virality is to spell out the practical value of what you offer. Your buyers will happily turn into ambassadors when you do a few things. Pay attention to their interests, wishes, doubts, and fears. People love when a brand remembers them, cares about them, and steps in to help. In other words, they want the gift list of fresh ideas in November, not in February. Make sure your insights and advice stand out in a sea of other information. After they use it and feel the win, they will feel obliged to pass it on. People help each other more when they are going through the same things. Make your audience feel special and valued. Personal offers, invites to events, and themed discounts help.\n\nSpeaking of discounts, which works better, naming the amount of money saved or the percentage. After a string of market studies, experts laid out the 100 rule. If a product costs less than one hundred dollars, show the discount as a percentage. When it costs more, it pays to name the dollar amount saved. A 10 percent discount on a fifty dollar pullover reads better than a sign that says you save five dollars. The same 10 percent off a five thousand dollar music system is less tempting than a sign that flashes five hundred dollars off.\n\nShow your audience the hidden value of your services, and they will stay loyal for a long time."
      },
      {
        title: 'Open up your customers through stories',
        text: "Stories have been part of human life for thousands of years. Our ancestors drew successful hunts on cave walls. As language and music grew, they shared stories by the fire and passed them on in song, handing down lessons and wisdom.\n\nWriting lifted storytelling to a new level. People could now write things down, save them for years, and carry them anywhere to share. The arrival of theater lifted the status and reach of stories even more. Actors playing roles made audiences live, cheer, and worry about the lives of people they had never met.\n\nHuman love for stories runs older than books, films, television, the internet, and, of course, seminars on how to tell a good story. That is why people from different cultures can find common ground by listening to and sharing stories that entertain and teach.\n\nPutting a business idea into practice has a lot in common with game design. Every customer wants to stand out from the other players, earn extra points, and feel like a winner.\n\nAds have become the shortest and most popular stories of our time. With only a few seconds to work with, creative teams try to make viewers feel what the people on screen feel and buy the product.\n\nSome ad campaigns have even played out like full TV series. The long face off between Pepsi and Coca Cola on the screen left few people cold. Fans waited for the next round and picked their side.\n\nOn the flip side, ads often bend reality to look their best, from how people look to how they live. The thin young models in ads for beauty products, clothes, or desserts do not speak to every viewer, and that gap can stir up disappointment and self image issues for some.\n\nSo, when you tell stories and spread your ideas, keep healthy human relationships in mind. Reach for people's feelings and experiences, not just the surface stuff. Let your audience be themselves and enjoy using your services."
      },
      {
        title: 'In closing',
        text: "Modern businesses and marketing campaigns should chase a useful kind of virality. You can set a strong example in a few ways. Find a fresh way to reach your audience, the way Steve Jobs did. Understand the real wishes of your customers, the way social worker Koreen Johannessen does. Surprise your buyers, the way Blendtec's Tom Dickson or journalist Denise Grady does. Pull people in with a one of a kind experience, the way the owners of the Please Don't Tell bar do.\n\nVery few things go viral by accident. Most of the time, virality is the result of a careful plan that takes care of current buyers and pulls in new ones.\n\nThe recipe is not hidden. People will pay attention to your services and pass them along when the products make them feel better. If your work stirs up good feelings and brings something new and useful, the spread grows fast. If you can also place your brand's story inside the wider story of human life and earn social proof, you will hold the keys to virality.\n\nStudy your audience, watch what your partners build, and try new things without fear. Most of all, enjoy your work. That energy will pass on to your customers.\n\nA short exercise. Put your idea to the test and lay out a plan to spread it. How many people know about it today. How will it make their lives better. What feelings does your product bring, and what story does it tell. Why would people want to tell others about it."
      }
    ]
  },

  'conversations-with-myself.json': {
    base: { id: 'conversations-with-myself', title: 'Conversations with Myself', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781613192084 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'To know a person, look at the private side',
        text: "We tend to see people through the lens of their public acts, their behavior, and even their speeches. What we see in public shapes a first view of who they are, but that view can be a mask. Conversations With Myself gives a sense of Mandela's private life, away from the cameras and the judgment of the crowd. It shows the kind of man he was outside the spotlight, with family, friends, acquaintances, and even in a small cell on his own.\n\nThis summary opens with the early chapters of Mandela's life. It looks at the ideas that shaped his core values, the way he acted, and even the beliefs he held until his last breath.\n\nLearning about others helps us pick up lessons that lift us and our relationships.\n\nMandela's life shows that most people are shaped by what they have been around for a long time. As a boy from the countryside, Mandela spent most of his early life in a village. He did not suddenly drop the habits of that life just because he moved west, where Western culture was louder. His life also shows that it is human nature to want to satisfy our curiosity, whether by asking those who came before us or by searching on our own. That search grows stronger when we meet people who share our passions or our minds. The quest can pull us into strange adventures, and, whether we see it or not, those adventures can help us face hard moments later on. Mandela's adventures as a boy helped him through his political fights. Knowing that nothing we pick up along the way is wasted is a powerful thing.\n\nOn the flip side, that knowledge can save us in the toughest moments. In this summary, you will learn how to look closely at yourself and how to grow through self review. You will also see how looking back at the past can help shape what comes next.\n\nThere is a wide respect, and even admiration, for those who stay humble and simple by nature and who hold quiet confidence in every person, no matter their place in life. As Nelson Mandela once said."
      },
      {
        title: 'Strong friendships help you grow',
        text: "During his years in prison, Mandela wrote about the many friendships he kept. One of them was with Lazar Sidelsky, a lawyer who hired Mandela as an articled clerk in 1942. Sidelsky showed Mandela many small acts of kindness and help whenever Mandela was in a tight spot.\n\nMandela's friends gave him company and comfort, especially in his anxious hours. Whether he needed help or just a break, Mandela always had people around. The friendships did not stop with the friend. They reached into the family, and the bonds grew stronger across generations.\n\nFor Mandela, friendship was a way to build himself up, and it also warned him about what to expect in a new place. For example, when he was in Johannesburg, a friend warned him about the gangs that roamed at night. They were groups that, when they raided a house, took anything of value. The warning let Mandela move fast when the moment came. The heads up did not take away the shock of the first run in, but it was a heads up all the same.\n\nFriendship fights off loneliness and isolation and gives people a chance to offer the company they need.\n\nThe pull of friendship is hard to overstate, because we are social beings. It is striking how talks with friends can sometimes make us forget the loneliness around us. So it helps to remember that everyone needs a friend, since no one is an island. You never know what saving grace a friend's words might bring. The truth is that friendships are a resource we cannot do without, whether we are prisoners, politicians, or anyone else.\n\nIn Mandela's words, the cell is an ideal place to learn to know yourself, to search the processes of your own mind and feelings with honesty and regularity.\n\nA short note. According to the United States Bureau of Justice Statistics, the number of prisoners who died in federal prison custody rose from 378 in 2018 to 381 in 2019."
      },
      {
        title: 'The need for applause can hold you back',
        text: "Like every other politician, Mandela had his moments of fame and the same hunger any ambitious person carries, to reach for more than he had. That hunger made him say and do things he would not have on a quiet day. The need to build a name and stay in the public eye let many things slide. For example, he wrote letters and books with no real reason except to keep his name in the room. Mandela's life shows how, as humans, we tend to break our own rules to win the praise of others. Whether we break them on purpose or by accident, we break them. Sometimes we want the applause of others as a way to pay for the stress that piles up in our work. This feeling is common, especially among social reformers, and in the chase for applause, they will knock down any platform they stand on. Still, anyone outside politics can find a way around it.\n\nDo not trade your values for praise and admiration. It usually backfires.\n\nPeople will lie and do whatever it takes to be held in high regard by the crowd or by the powers above them. A good example is when Nelson Mandela had to be moved from Robben Island just two weeks after he arrived. Lies were told about how the move was for safety, when the real reason ran deeper into politics. It is no surprise that the hunger for more is strong among people in power. Everyone wants fame and a presence that makes them feel untouchable. That is why people want to be feared, and they will do anything to get there. It helps to know that no matter how much you want the applause of others, other people should not be the tool you use to get it."
      },
      {
        title: 'Home and family give us a sense of safety',
        text: "Home is such a common word that few people feel the weight in it. Nelson Mandela wrote about how no place feels like home. He tried his best to describe the rush of joy that hits when you reach the streets of your hometown. It does not matter how long you have been away, even if it seems nothing has changed. The feeling of being home cannot be put fully into words. When you are near the one you call mother, the joy grows deeper, and that joy carries confidence with it.\n\nNo matter how old we get, we feel a kind of childlike thrill when we get back home.\n\nAt home, you feel stronger and freer. For example, during one of Mandela's visits to his hometown of Mthatha in South Africa, he had a face off with a security officer, without thinking about what could come of it. Being home also seems to bring back the things you have set aside or stopped paying attention to. For instance, Mandela was reminded during a visit that his mother was no longer young and needed help with some things. He felt a pang of regret because she was living alone, far from town, a wish that is common among older people. Still, wanting to be alone did not mean she was fine on her own and looked after. No matter how far we are from home, it helps to look back once in a while. We will see, sooner or later, that the more time we spend away from home and family, the more our daily routine wears us down. There is a kind of warmth that home gives. You can find something close, but it will not be the same. In the end, the weight of family cannot be overstated."
      },
      {
        title: 'Hold your beliefs, reflect, and grow your mind',
        text: "We should not treat the power of conviction lightly. Once you are sure of a decision, it can take something stronger to move you. Whether you are facing death or something less grim, conviction helps you keep your stand on what is possible, no matter how dark it looks. Mandela writes about a mild run in with this in his talks with Ahmed Kathrada, an anti apartheid activist, politician, and political prisoner. He describes how his conviction fed his principles, standards, and wishes, and how it prepared him to die for them if needed.\n\nWhen you are alone, it pays to think. When you think, you get the chance to look back, and that leads to weighty, life changing choices. Thinking grows the reach of your mind. In a letter to Hilda Bernstein, an author, artist, and anti apartheid and women's rights activist, dated July 8, 1985, Mandela shared his view that reflection had started to feel important to him. Even with all the knowledge that new tech seems to offer, and the easier work it does, it is clear that the brain's power is far more reliable than many of the tools we lean on.\n\nReflection is a key part of growth, because it lets you shape the future with more care.\n\nThe best way to train your brain to reach further is to use it more, and the science backs that up. Our brains should never reach a point where they go to waste from lack of use. How much we have used our brain is something to check during self review. It is also a key part of how we grow as people.\n\nIn Mandela's words, western civilisation has not fully worn away his African roots, and he has not forgotten the days of his childhood when the community would gather around the elders to drink in their wisdom and experience."
      },
      {
        title: 'Standing for justice ripples out to others',
        text: "Most people do not want to take a stand for truth and justice. Even though it may sound harsh, it is something every person on the surface is prone to. The effects of standing for justice are hard to predict. Sometimes the stand is productive and brings a clear win, and sometimes it does not. For example, a woman who takes a stand for justice is sent to jail and has to live with the pain of being separated from her kids and husband. While she may be able to handle the cost to herself, the same is not true for the people she has had to leave behind. Her kids, in particular, would have to deal with the loneliness of having no mother at home. On top of that, there would be little or no direction as they grow. That lack of direction can split the family in more ways than we imagine.\n\nFor Nelson Mandela, watching his mother as a child helped him on his political path. The bravery and strength he saw in her as a boy fed his own fire and drive. In a way, she was his political hero.\n\nThe stand for justice is a hard road that only the bravest hearts can walk.\n\nA careful self review helps you weigh how your choices, especially in politics, hit the people around you. You should also be able to measure whether you can bear the cost of those choices. Standing firm for your beliefs can be a powerful thing, but many people cannot handle the cost, not just for themselves, but for the people they love."
      },
      {
        title: 'Wrapping up',
        text: "Nelson Mandela writes about many things in his letters, from his view of friendships and family to his thoughts on his rivals. The fact is that there is always something to learn. Life always has something to show us. It may be from watching an animal on the road going about its day, or from seeing the pain of people worn down by war. What matters is not just what life shows us, but what we can pick up and truly learn from each of those moments.\n\nThe habit of self review is core to being human, and without it, our growth in many areas would stall. The weight of friendships and family cannot be overstated, especially when the people in them are real. The more we grow as people, the more the value of these clusters sinks in. Finally, as people, no matter how rough the people we meet may seem, we should always give them a chance. We are not perfect, and there is always room to grow. It helps to know that as we go through life, we will meet people who will play real parts in our story. Whether we see it early or not, the people around us tend to shape our lives in one way or another.\n\nA short exercise. If you live far from home and your parents are still alive, it pays to visit home as often as you can. That way, your parents, especially if they are old, get company, and you will see their current needs. If you are new to an area, get to know the people around you and build friendships. Do not pull away into isolation, because in the end, you cannot do it on your own."
      }
    ]
  },

  'coronavirus-and-business.json': {
    base: { id: 'coronavirus-and-business', title: 'Coronavirus and Business', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781613715535 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Leading through the crisis',
        text: "Putting together a strong supply chain response during a pandemic is hard. We are taught to be ready for the worst, but once a crisis lands, the plan often falls short. Still, there are ways to act, even when you are not fully ready.\n\nStart with your people. Put your staff first. If you do not already have a way to reach them, set one up. Think about changing how work gets done.\n\nLean on healthy doubt. A cool head and good judgment matter for anyone trying to make sense of a messy situation. As the story unfolds, new facts come out, so even official sources may carry mixed messages.\n\nLocal contacts can share useful signals. Keep those ties strong.\n\nRun outage drills to map out surprise scenarios. Picture and act out how your company would work under pressure from unlikely angles. It may cost time and money, but the lessons can leave your business stronger.\n\nBuild a core emergency operations center, or EOC. Most firms have something like this, but often only at the corporate or business unit level. A wider EOC that reaches every level of the company is needed.\n\nFew businesses stand on their own. Most lean on stakeholders, customers, and supply chains. To handle the supply chain impact during a crisis, understand your full supply network, including suppliers further up the chain, so you can size up likely impacts when a crisis hits. Know your weak spots and pool the risk. Drop supply chains that put your business at risk. Write business continuity plans that cover transport, communication, supply, and cash flow. Take care of your people, since they also need a backup plan. Plan for more automation and flexible work to handle staffing gaps.\n\nWhen you build a continuity plan, include not just key stakeholders but also suppliers and customers.\n\nReshape your supply chain. Use dual sourcing to lower the risk of disruption. Move to local sourcing so production sits closer to local suppliers. That path has its own risks, but with sources spread out, transport costs tend to drop."
      },
      {
        title: 'Business is changing. Will you adapt or fall behind',
        text: "The Covid 19 crisis is still taking lives every day and pushing public health systems to the limit. Vaccines are rolling out, and the picture should improve, but the timeline is still unclear. The pandemic has hit every part of life, and the economy is one of them. Stronger economies absorb the blow, while weaker ones shrink. No matter the size, businesses are facing the need to change or close up shop.\n\nThe Harvard Business Review has laid out a set of guidelines for responding to fast moving events, communicating, and pulling out the lessons that matter.\n\nCollect the freshest data. Things are moving faster than ever. At first, the virus looked like China's problem, and many thought China had it under control. Today, a new strain is in play, and different countries keep taking turns leading the grim numbers. Sharing updates each day is key to staying relevant and keeping a hold on your situation in the bigger picture.\n\nUpdate your view of the world every day, not just to refresh the numbers, but to reshape how you see things.\n\nTake hype in stride. Information changes fast. We tend to brush off soft signals and over react to loud ones. We need to take a steadier view. Whatever it is, we tend to make it bigger than it is. Before you act on a piece of news, check how reliable the source is.\n\nInformation alone does not raise awareness. Today, we have more information than ever. Many employers think that is enough for their staff, but companies need to share the right facts and the meaning behind them, or people will read it the wrong way, get confused, and waste time in pointless debate.\n\nPick your experts and forecasts with care. Epidemiology, virology, public health, and other fields are central to clearing up complex information. Still, experts often disagree on the big questions, and that is because we are dealing with cases no one has seen before. It always helps to look at more than one source, and every reliable source should be guided by expert view.\n\nStay flexible about the state of things. Large businesses are rarely nimble, with many staff and a thick layer of process. Managers often hold off on sharing plans until they are fully sure, and then they hesitate to change them for fear of looking unsure or stirring up trouble inside the firm.\n\nPay close attention to a few key areas. Communication, so policies reach people fast, clearly, and evenly. Employee needs, so that travel limits and health concerns are met, with a resource hub for the must have information. Travel, with clear rules on destinations, reasons, approvals, and updates. Remote work, with a clear plan for how people will work and when the plan will be reviewed. Supply chain stability, by building safety stocks and finding backup sources, working with suppliers on shared problems and interim plans."
      },
      {
        title: 'Questions to ask as you respond to the crisis',
        text: "The coronavirus outbreak is a reminder for companies to take a hard look at their plans for staff, operations, and customer safety. In response to the spread, companies should sit with a few key questions.\n\nHow can we keep workers from being exposed on the job. The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention advises staff to stay home when they have respiratory symptoms or a fever over 100.4 F, wash hands for at least 20 seconds or use hand sanitizer, leave work if symptoms show up, and cover coughs and sneezes with a tissue, elbow, or shoulder.\n\nWhen should workers or visitors stay out of the workplace. Staff with coronavirus symptoms should not come in. Managers need to remember that the virus is highly contagious. They should send an employee showing signs of Covid 19 home right away. Visitors with symptoms or at high risk should be moved away from other staff, guided on how to leave the workplace, sent for a medical check, and kept apart from others.\n\nIf Covid 19 spreads out of control, companies should use thermal scanners to check temperatures and turn away anyone reading over 100.4 F.\n\nCompanies are advised to keep people out for 14 days if they have been exposed to the virus or have just come from a high risk area.\n\nFor meetings, cap the number of attendees and ask older staff or those with chronic conditions to join virtually, as the Harvard Business Review notes.\n\nWhat will our benefits look like if employees work from home, or if we shut the site. With more people falling ill, the number of staff working from home is growing. Many companies have already updated their policies, while others are still working it out. Employers need to see that remote work can be done just as carefully as work in the office. Staff should not be punished for taking sick leave. Guaranteeing that builds trust and leads to honest self reporting, which cuts down on exposure.\n\nCovid 19 spreads mostly through droplets from coughing and sneezing.\n\nA side note. Around 60 percent of employers in a Harvard Business Review survey said they had set up the right conditions for staff to work from home, with 46 percent already doing so and 13 percent planning to."
      },
      {
        title: 'Make your supply chain pandemic ready',
        text: "Putting together a strong supply chain response during a pandemic is hard. We are taught to be ready for the worst, but once a crisis lands, the plan often falls short. Still, there are ways to act, even when you are not fully ready.\n\nStart with your people. Put your staff first. If you do not already have a way to reach them, set one up. Think about changing how work gets done.\n\nLean on healthy doubt. A cool head and good judgment matter for anyone trying to make sense of a messy situation. As the story unfolds, new facts come out, so even official sources may carry mixed messages.\n\nLocal contacts can share useful signals. Keep those ties strong.\n\nRun outage drills to map out surprise scenarios. Picture and act out how your company would work under pressure from unlikely angles. It may cost time and money, but the lessons can leave your business stronger.\n\nBuild a core emergency operations center, or EOC. Most firms have something like this, but often only at the corporate or business unit level. A wider EOC that reaches every level of the company is needed.\n\nFew businesses stand on their own. Most lean on stakeholders, customers, and supply chains. To handle the supply chain impact during a crisis, understand your full supply network, including suppliers further up the chain, so you can size up likely impacts when a crisis hits. Know your weak spots and pool the risk. Drop supply chains that put your business at risk. Write business continuity plans that cover transport, communication, supply, and cash flow. Take care of your people, since they also need a backup plan. Plan for more automation and flexible work to handle staffing gaps.\n\nWhen you build a continuity plan, include not just key stakeholders but also suppliers and customers.\n\nReshape your supply chain. Use dual sourcing to lower the risk of disruption. Move to local sourcing so production sits closer to local suppliers. That path has its own risks, but with sources spread out, transport costs tend to drop."
      },
      {
        title: 'Try these moves before laying people off',
        text: "During a hard stretch like the coronavirus outbreak, the urge to cut costs is understandable. Leaders have a duty to keep their businesses alive. They have to make the right call, and sometimes a hard one, to handle the damage from the disaster. If they pull it off, the company will come back stronger and create more value. So, before you start cutting and laying off, take a look at the moves below.\n\nCommunicate openly. In hard times, many leaders worry that if they admit the truth, their teams will see them as weak. Some even fear that staff will start looking for work elsewhere. They choose to act like everything is fine and that the hard truth has no impact on the business. That is probably the worst move a leadership team can make. Admitting that things are rough shows that you are a steady, strong leader. It also builds trust between the top team and the rest of the staff, with the message that whatever comes, they can carry it together.\n\nSet clear goals that match the company's reality. Avoid empty lines you do not believe in. Speak from the heart, and your staff will feel respected and safe.\n\nShare the pain. As we said, a leader has to be ready to make tough calls. If cuts are coming, include yourself. If you do not, your staff will be unhappy, and some will hold it against you. They will feel like prey, forced to give up everything while the CEO does not.\n\nTalk with clients about keeping the work going. Not every project has to end. Some can just pause for a while.\n\nBring employees in to crowdsource ideas. Crowdsourcing, in company terms, means asking your staff for ideas. You may worry that people will pitch ideas that cannot be done. If you ignore them, the people who raised them will feel brushed off. The whole process can feel heavy. You may also fear that letting your team speak up will dent your image as a strong leader. These concerns are real, but the gains from this move outweigh them. When you ask your staff, you make them feel seen and important. The many minds, many ideas rule has a flip side. You may pick up valuable advice.\n\nLook at every option. Before you push through layoffs, look at less obvious ways to cut costs. You can offer some staff a part time schedule, or unpaid leave, framed as a sabbatical. These moves are not fun, but they help people keep their jobs in hard times."
      },
      {
        title: 'How to lead a remote team',
        text: "In response to the unease from Covid 19, many companies told their staff to work from home. For most of them, remote work was a brand new experience. Many daily routines had to be done a little differently. If only there had been time to design and test policies in advance. The pandemic did not wait, and there was no spare moment to pick the best ways to handle the new work setup. Managers have research based moves to lift the focus and output of remote staff. Still, remote work comes with real hurdles.\n\nLack of in person supervision. Many managers worry that their staff will slack off when no one is watching in person. The question of trust and personal responsibility comes up again. Trust and responsibility are a two way street between a manager and an employee.\n\nRemote workers who have never met in person are less likely to extend understanding in stressful moments.\n\nLack of access to information. Getting information from coworkers can take longer than usual. In an office, we are usually less distracted and can focus better. It just takes time to get used to a remote rhythm.\n\nSocial isolation. Many employees live alone. Being forced to work from home can lead to depression, since there is no face to face contact with other people.\n\nDistractions at home. Employees with families or roommates have a different set of complaints. For some of them, those around them are a steady distraction.\n\nNow, here are moves to support remote staff.\n\nSet up structured daily check ins. Run daily calls with your remote staff. Choose one on one talks or group calls, depending on the team.\n\nOffer a range of communication tools. Email alone is not enough. It helps to have richer tech for remote work. Video calls give people visual signals they would get face to face.\n\nSet clear rules of engagement. Lay out a set of rules to organize remote work. Staff will find it clearer and be more productive when they have real guidelines. They will appreciate it if you set the means, the frequency, and the best time for engagement."
      },
      {
        title: 'Communicate early and often through a crisis',
        text: "In unpredictable times, leaders face questions they cannot answer. Those in charge need to communicate fast throughout the crisis. Even if you are still trying to gauge the size of the problem, honesty and openness can help protect the trust you have built. Be understanding, because you and your teams are in it together.\n\nTry to see the situation from your team's point of view and show empathy.\n\nSet up one team for central communication. Decentralized communication can work in big, complex organizations, where small units act like startups inside a larger firm. Put together a crisis response team with key people from different departments. In an emergency, a focused team of five to seven is essential. Include a leader, a corporate communications person, an HR executive, and a specialist in the relevant field. The team should meet often to handle the situation as it changes, be the main source of crisis information, share updates on key developments, stay transparent by sharing what is known and what is not, and keep messages brief and to the point. Avoid long, complex messages from health experts or lawyers.\n\nStudies show that leaders play a special role in cutting employee anxiety, as the Harvard Business Review notes.\n\nKeep employees in the loop. Staff turn ideas into action and act as the face of the business. Without enough information about the company's direction in hard times, staff can send the wrong message to the outside world. The company should adopt a policy of sharing all available information with staff in a clear way.\n\nTo talk with employees, companies should post information often where everyone can see it, in person or online, lay out the decision making process for travel and remote work, not hold back on reaching out at least three times a week, and share updates as new information comes in.\n\nUpdate customers on a steady rhythm. Customers need a custom approach to communication, focused on highlighting customer priorities, with a letter to grocery shoppers listing every safety measure put in place during the pandemic. Make room for relief where you can. Travel and flight companies can lean on this. Skip the sales pitch and lead with empathy."
      },
      {
        title: 'Looking back',
        text: "Covid 19 has taken many lives and changed most of our daily habits beyond recognition. Many of us had no choice but to work from home. Some took it as a gift, with more time to spend with family. Others living alone found it tough, as their social life and in person contact faded.\n\nThese times are hard on everyone, with no exception. Still, we can work together to make each day a little easier on each other. In our work lives, we should say what we feel, what we fear, and what can be done to soften the hard conditions. As an employee, support your coworkers and chase company goals that may be shifting faster than usual. If you are a leader, be open, share the information on hand, and listen to your staff. Compassion and empathy matter more than chasing profit by any means.\n\nThe crisis can also bring out the best in people and open up new chances. We may have already learned to be more responsible and more respectful of each other. One of the biggest lessons for businesses is that being humane is good for your reputation and your returns. When your staff, partners, and customers feel that you put their needs first and take their worries seriously, they will do their best to back you in hard times and stay loyal for years to come.\n\nA short exercise. In the middle of a crisis, we are all vulnerable. Beyond our work lives, we need to look after our minds and emotions. The authors of this book share a few ways to build resilience.\n\nCalm your mind. When you quiet the loop of worst case scenarios, even for a moment, your chances of understanding what is going on go up. Try familiar practices like yoga and meditation. If those feel too advanced, start with slow breathing. Make your exhale at least two seconds longer than your inhale.\n\nDistract yourself. When the feelings feel too much to handle, switch to an activity that needs little thought. You can look out the window and count the trees in your yard, finally clean your desk, or run out for a small item.\n\nSupport others. We are all in this together, and the bottom line is that we need to be kind and supportive. Being kind means being willing to make the first move. Be the first to reach out and build a real connection with someone who needs it."
      }
    ]
  }
};
